1. Problem Statement
Insurance companies face significant financial losses due to fraudulent claims, including staged accidents, inflated
repair bills, and false medical or property damage claims. Manual investigation is slow, inconsistent, and unable 
to scale with increasing claim volumes. 
This results in:
i.) High claim leakage (payouts on fraudulent claims)
ii.) Delayed genuine claim settlements
iii.) Increased operational investigation costsi
iv) Customer dissatisfaction due to long processing times
2. Proposed AI Solution
An AI-driven Claim Fraud Detection System that automatically flags suspicious insurance claims in near real-time 
using historical claim patterns, behavioral signals, and anomaly detection techniques.
The system will:
Score incoming claims based on fraud likelihood, Prioritize claims for human investigation, Continuously learn from 
investigator feedback, Integrate with existing claims management systems
3. Required Data
To build an effective model, the following data is required:
i.) Structured Data
ii.) Claim history (amount, type, frequency)
iii.) Policyholder profile (age, location, tenure, coverage type)
iv.) Claim settlement outcomes (approved/rejected/fraud confirmed)
v.) Historical fraud labels (investigation results)
Unstructured Data
Claim documents (invoices, medical reports, repair bills)
Photos/videos of damage (if applicable)
Adjuster notes and investigation reports
Behavioral & External Data
Claim submission patterns
Device/IP/location metadata
External fraud databases (blacklists, known fraud rings)
4. Model Recommendation
A hybrid machine learning approach is recommended:
Gradient Boosting Models (e.g., XGBoost / LightGBM)
Best for structured tabular insurance data; high interpretability and strong performance on classification tasks.
Neural Network-based anomaly detection (optional enhancement)
Useful for identifying unseen fraud patterns.
Text embeddings (NLP models like BERT) for extracting signals from claim descriptions and documents.
Why this approach:
Handles mixed structured + unstructured data
Balances accuracy and interpretability (critical in regulated insurance domain)
Scalable for large claim volumes
5. Expected Business Impact
20–40% reduction in fraud-related losses
Improved claim processing speed through automated triaging
Reduced investigation workload by prioritizing high-risk claims
Higher customer satisfaction due to faster approval of genuine claims
Better regulatory compliance with consistent fraud detection logic
6. Risks and Mitigation Plan
1. False Positives (Legitimate claims flagged as fraud)
Risk: Customer dissatisfaction and reputational damage
Mitigation: Human-in-the-loop review, threshold tuning, explainable AI outputs
2. Bias in Model Predictions
Risk: Certain customer groups may be unfairly flagged
Mitigation: Bias audits, fairness constraints, diverse training data
3. Over-reliance on AI decisions
Risk: Automated rejection without human validation
Mitigation: Mandatory investigator approval for high-impact decisions
4. Data Privacy and Compliance Risks
Risk: Exposure of sensitive customer and health data
Mitigation: Data anonymization, encryption, strict access control, GDPR/IRDAI compliance
5. Concept Drift (fraud patterns evolve over time)
Risk: Model performance degrades
Mitigation: Continuous retraining pipeline and drift monitoring
7. SummaryThis solution enables insurance providers to shift from reactive fraud detection to a proactive, AI-powered risk
scoring system. By combining structured data modeling with NLP and anomaly detection, insurers can significantly
reduce fraud losses while improving operational efficiency and customer experience.
